Below is a **single, self‑contained unit** that you can drop in a small OCaml project and compile with `ocamlc/ocamlopt` together with a C++ compiler (e.g. `g++ -std=c++17`).  

It consists of  

* `pcapng.mli` – the public OCaml interface you will expose to users,  
* `pcapng.ml` – a thin wrapper that only declares the external primitives,  
* `pcapng_stubs.cpp` – the C‑C++ glue code that talks to the C++ `libpcapng` iterator and marshals data to/from OCaml.

You can keep the three files in the same directory and build them with something like:

```sh
ocamlc -c pcapng.mli
ocamlc -c pcapng.ml
g++ -c -I$(ocamlc -where) -std=c++17 -fPIC pcapng_stubs.cpp
ocamlc -a -o libpcapng.cma pcapng.cmo pcapng_stubs.o
```

(If you prefer native code, replace `ocamlc`/`.cma` with `ocamlopt`/`.cmxa`.)

---

## 1.  `pcapng.mli` – the public OCaml interface

```ocaml
(** {1 OCaml bindings for libpcapng} *)

(** An opaque handle to a pcapng file.  The value is managed by the
    runtime – you must call {!close} when you are done. *)
type t

(** A single captured frame.  Only a tiny subset of the fields that
    libpcapng makes available is exposed here; you can always extend
    the record later. *)
type frame = {
  timestamp    : int64;   (** nanoseconds since the Unix epoch *)
  captured_len : int;     (** number of bytes stored in the file *)
  original_len : int;     (** original length of the packet on the wire *)
  data         : bytes;   (** raw packet bytes (exactly [captured_len] long) *)
}

(** Open a pcapng file for reading.  Raises [Failure] if the file cannot
    be opened or is not a valid pcapng file. *)
val open_file : string -> t

(** Close a file opened with {!open_file}.  After this call the handle
    must no longer be used. *)
val close : t -> unit

(** Iterate over *all* frames in the file, applying the supplied OCaml
    function to each frame.  The iteration runs entirely in C++ – the
    OCaml callback is invoked for each frame, but the traversal itself
    does **not** allocate any intermediate OCaml data structures.  The
    callback may raise; the exception is propagated to the caller and
    iteration stops. *)
val iter : t -> (frame -> unit) -> unit

(** Same as {!iter} but the callback can decide when to stop.  The
    callback must return [true] to continue, [false] to abort early.
    The function returns [true] if the whole file was traversed,
    [false] if the callback asked to stop early.  Exceptions from the
    callback are propagated. *)
val iter_until : t -> (frame -> bool) -> bool
```

